The keyof Operator

The `keyof` operator takes an object type and produces a union of its keys (property names).

### Basic Usage

```typescript
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
}

type PersonKeys = keyof Person;
// "name" | "age" | "email"

let key: PersonKeys = "name";
key = "age";
key = "email";
// key = "salary"; // Error
```

### keyof with Index Signatures

```typescript
interface StringMap {
  [key: string]: unknown;
}

type MapKeys = keyof StringMap;
// string | number
```

### keyof with typeof

```typescript
const colors = {
  red: "#FF0000",
  green: "#00FF00",
  blue: "#0000FF"
} as const;

type ColorKey = keyof typeof colors;
// "red" | "green" | "blue"

type ColorValue = (typeof colors)[ColorKey];
// "#FF0000" | "#00FF00" | "#0000FF"
```

### Practical Use: Type-Safe Property Access

```typescript
function getValue<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {
  return obj[key];
}

const user = { id: 1, name: "Alice" };
const id = getValue(user, "id"); // number
const name = getValue(user, "name"); // string
```

### keyof with Mapped Types

```typescript
type Optional<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]?: T[K];
};

type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K];
};
```

> **Key Point:** `keyof` is essential for creating type-safe accessor functions and mapped types.

codeExample:
interface ApiConfig {
  baseUrl: string;
  timeout: number;
  retries: number;
  headers: Record<string, string>;
}

// Type-safe config updater
function updateConfig<K extends keyof ApiConfig>(
  config: ApiConfig,
  key: K,
  value: ApiConfig[K]
): void {
  config[key] = value;
  console.log(`Updated ${key} to ${value}`);
}

const config: ApiConfig = {
  baseUrl: "https://api.example.com",
  timeout: 5000,
  retries: 3,
  headers: {}
};

updateConfig(config, "timeout", 10000);
updateConfig(config, "baseUrl", "https://new-api.com");

// Get all keys
type ConfigKeys = keyof ApiConfig;
// "baseUrl" | "timeout" | "retries" | "headers"
